  "prompt": "What is the best way to remove permanent marker from a countertop?",
  "response": "Removing permanent marker from a countertop can be done effectively using a few different methods. Here are some options:\n\n1. **Rubbing Alcohol or Isopropyl Alcohol:**\n   - Dampen a cloth or paper towel with rubbing alcohol.\n   - Gently rub the stained area until the marker begins to lift.\n   - Wipe the area with a clean damp cloth afterward to remove any residue.\n\n2. **Acetone or Nail Polish Remover:**\n   - Apply a small amount of acetone to a cloth.\n   - Blot the marker stain, being careful not to damage the countertop surface.\n   - Clean the area with soap and water afterward to eliminate any acetone residue.\n\n3. **Dry-Erase Marker:**\n   - Color over the permanent marker stain with a dry-erase marker.\n   - Immediately wipe it away with a dry cloth or eraser. This can sometimes lift the permanent marker along with it.\n\n4. **Baking Soda and Water Paste:**\n   - Mix baking soda with a small amount of water to create a paste.\n   - Apply the paste to the stain and gently rub it with a soft cloth.\n   - Rinse with water afterward.\n\n5. **Magic Eraser:**\n   - Use a Magic Eraser or a similar melamine foam cleaner.\n   - Wet the Eraser slightly and scrub the marker stain gently.\n   - Wipe clean after the stain is removed.\n\n6. **Vinegar and Cornstarch:**\n   - Mix equal parts of vinegar and cornstarch to form a paste.\n   - Apply to the marker stain, let it sit for a few minutes, then wipe it away.\n\n**Note:** Always test any cleaning method on a small, inconspicuous area of the countertop first to ensure it does not damage the surface. If the countertop is made of a sensitive material like granite or marble, avoid harsh chemicals and stick to gentler methods.",
